<h2>Key to Cactaceae</h2><a href='http://herbaria4.herb.berkeley.edu/eflora_display.php?tid=79'><h3>View taxon page for Cactaceae</h3></a><blockquote><h3></h3>
<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 0 ;"><a href="#NK1'">1.</a><a name="NK1."> </a> Stem regularly segmented; areoles with glochids; seeds tightly encased within bone-like aril, &plusmn; white when dry

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 7 ;"><a href="#NK2'">2.</a><a name="NK2."> </a> Stem segments flat, tubercles 0 to &plusmn; developed; spine surface not separating <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=10641">.....&nbsp;OPUNTIA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 7 ;"><a href="#NK2.">2'</a><a name="NK2'"> </a> Stem segments cylindric to club-like, generally tubercled; spine surface sheath-like, generally separating and late-deciduous

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK3'">3.</a><a name="NK3."> </a> Spines not flat; spine sheath 0 or fully separating; mature plant generally 0.3&ndash;4 m <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=68351">.....&nbsp;CYLINDROPUNTIA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK3.">3'</a><a name="NK3'"> </a> Major spines flat; spine sheath separating only from tip; mature plant generally &lt; 0.25 m <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=82499">.....&nbsp;GRUSONIA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 0 ;"><a href="#NK1.">1'</a><a name="NK1'"> </a> Stem not regularly segmented; glochids 0; dry seeds generally black to &plusmn; red-brown, lacking a &plusmn; white bone-like aril

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 7 ;"><a href="#NK4'">4.</a><a name="NK4."> </a> Largest spines with transverse ridges; spines generally 2&ndash;5 mm diam near base, rigid

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK5'">5.</a><a name="NK5."> </a> Ovary, generally stem tip densely woolly, obscuring epidermis, ovary scales tapered to sharp tips <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9219">.....&nbsp;ECHINOCACTUS</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK5.">5'</a><a name="NK5'"> </a> Ovary, stem tip glabrous, only areoles woolly, ovary scales generally rounded <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=10633">.....&nbsp;FEROCACTUS</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 7 ;"><a href="#NK4.">4'</a><a name="NK4'"> </a> Largest spines smooth or longitudinally ridged; spines generally &lt; 2 mm diam near base, rigid or not, thin, flexible if > 2 mm wide

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK6'">6.</a><a name="NK6."> </a> Stem ribs 0 or inconspicuous, tubercles prominent

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 21 ;"><a href="#NK7'">7.</a><a name="NK7."> </a> Spines all straight to &plusmn; curved; stem tubercles with woolly, adaxial groove connecting spine cluster to axillary flower areole <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9218">.....&nbsp;CORYPHANTHA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 21 ;"><a href="#NK7.">7'</a><a name="NK7'"> </a> Some spines in each areole generally hook-shaped; stem tubercles not adaxially grooved <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=10638">.....&nbsp;MAMMILLARIA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 14 ;"><a href="#NK6.">6'</a><a name="NK6'"> </a> Stem ribs prominent, tubercles &plusmn; 0 or prominent on ribs

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 21 ;"><a href="#NK8'">8.</a><a name="NK8."> </a> Stem > 30 cm diam, branched but generally not in basal 1.5&ndash;2 m; perianth generally white <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9216">.....&nbsp;CARNEGIEA</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 21 ;"><a href="#NK8.">8'</a><a name="NK8'"> </a> Stem &lt; 15 cm diam, not branched, or branched in basal 1.5 m; perianth variously colored, but generally not white

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 28 ;"><a href="#NK9'">9.</a><a name="NK9."> </a> Stem length > 8 &times; diam; fruit persistent when empty, densely spiny; coastal <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9215">.....&nbsp;BERGEROCACTUS</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 28 ;"><a href="#NK9.">9'</a><a name="NK9'"> </a> Stem length &lt; 6 &times; diam; fruit not persistent when empty, spineless or spines deciduous; inland

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 35 ;"><a href="#NK10'">10.</a><a name="NK10."> </a> Flowers lateral; ovary minutely scaly, spiny, spines deciduous in clusters; stem soft-fleshy, branches 1&ndash;500 <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9220">.....&nbsp;ECHINOCEREUS</a>

<P class="keyText" style="padding-left : 35 ;"><a href="#NK10.">10'</a><a name="NK10'"> </a> Flowers at stem tip or nearly so; ovary scaly, spineless; stem &plusmn; hard, branches 0&ndash;few (more if stem damaged) <a href="/cgi-bin/get_IJM.pl?tid=9221">.....&nbsp;SCLEROCACTUS</a></blockquote><P>
<a href="&#109;&#97;&#105;&#108;to:rosatti&#064;berkeley.edu?subject=eFlora comment"><font size=3 color="red">Contact/Feedback</font></a>
